  <subsection permid="KVE">
    <title>Horizontal Lines and Vertical Lines</title>
    <p permid="yeJ">
      We learned in <xref ref="section-standard-form">Section</xref>
      that all lines can be written in <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref>.
      When either <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> equal <m>0</m>,
      we end up with a horizontal or vertical line, as we will soon see.
      Let's take the standard form line equation,
      <m>Ax+Bx=C</m>, and one at a time let <m>A=0</m> and <m>B=0</m> and simplify each equation.
    </p>

    <p permid="elS">
      <md permid="vkd">
        <mrow>Ax+By\amp=C\amp Ax+By\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>\substitute{0}x+By\amp=C\amp Ax+\substitute{0}y\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>By\amp=C\amp Ax\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{C}{B}\amp x\amp=\divideunder{C}{A}</mrow>
        <mrow>y\amp=k\amp x\amp=h</mrow>
      </md>
      At the end we just renamed the constant numbers <m>\frac{C}{B}</m> and
      <m>\frac{C}{A}</m> to <m>k</m> and <m>h</m> because of tradition.
      What is important, is that you view <m>h</m> and <m>k</m>
      (as well as <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>)
      as constants:
      numbers that have some specific value and don't change in the context of one problem.
    </p>

    <p permid="Ktb">
      Think about just one of these last equations: <m>y=k</m>.
      It says that the <m>y</m>-value is the same no matter where you are on the line.
      If you wanted to plot points on this line,
      you are free to move far to the left or far to the right on the <m>x</m>-axis,
      but then you always move up
      (or down)
      to make the <m>y</m>-value equal <m>k</m>.
      What does such a line look like?
    </p>

    <example permid="MKR">
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="xBT">

        <stack>
          <p permid="tQp">
            Let's plot the line with equation <m>y=3</m>.
            (Note that this is the same as <m>0x+1y=3</m>.)
          </p>
          <p permid="ZXy">
            To plot some points, it doesn't matter what <m>x</m>-values we use.
            All that matters is that <m>y</m> is
            <em>always</em> <m>3</m>.
          </p>
        </stack>

        <figure permid="mlQ">
          <caption><m>y=3</m></caption>
          <image permid="hQs">
            <description>a horizontal line at y=3</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(4,0) (5,0) (5,3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0) (1,3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-1,0) (-2,0) (-2,3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-5,0) (-6,0) (-6,3)};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(5,3) (1,3) (-2,3) (-6,3)};
                    \addplot[firstcurve]{3};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
      <p permid="GeH">
        A line like this is <term>horizontal</term>,
            <idx><h>horizontal line</h></idx>
        parallel to the horizontal axis.
        All lines with an equation in the form
        <me permid="brm">
          y=k
        </me>
        (or, in standard form, <m>0x+By=C</m>) are <term>horizontal</term>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example permid="sSa">
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" oldpermid="dJc">

        <stack>
          <p>
            Let's plot the line with equation <m>x=5</m>.
            Points on the line always have <m>x=5</m>, so if we wanted to make a table for plotting points,
            we are <em>required</em> to make all of the <m>x</m>-values be <m>5</m>.
            From there, we have complete freedom to let <m>y</m> take any value.
            Here we take some random <m>y</m>-values.
          </p>

          <tabular>
            <col right="minor"/>
            <col/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

          <p>
            These points are plotted in <xref ref="figure-vertical-line-example">Figure</xref>.
          </p>
        </stack>

        <figure xml:id="figure-vertical-line-example" permid="KOA">
          <caption><m>x=5</m></caption>
          <image permid="NXB">
            <description>a vertical line at x=5</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,5)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,1)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,-2)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,-6)};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(5,5) (5,1) (5,-2) (5,-6)};
                    \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(5,-7) (5,7)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        Note that the equation for this line is the same as <m>x+0y=5</m>.
        An alternative for making a table is to choose our <m>y</m>-values first and substitute them into the equation.
      </p>

      <sidebyside>
        <tabular>
          <col/>
          <col right="minor"/>
          <col/>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell><m>x+0y=5\implies x=5</m></cell>
            <cell>Ordered Pair</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
            <cell><m>x+0(-6)=5\implies x=5</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(5,-6)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>x+0(-2)=5\implies x=5</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(5,-2)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>x+0(1)=5\implies x=5</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(5,1)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
            <cell><m>x+0(5)=5\implies x=5</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(5,5)</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        In each case no matter what value <m>y</m> is,
        we find that the equation tells us that <m>x=5</m>.
      </p>

      <p permid="eHr">
        A line like this is <term>vertical</term>,
            <idx><h>vertical line</h></idx>
        parallel to the vertical axis.
        All lines with an equation in the form
        <me permid="Hyv">
          x=h
        </me>
        (or, in standard form, <m>Ax+0y=C</m>) are vertical.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example permid="YZj">
      <title>Zero Slope</title>
      <p permid="qVJ">
        In <xref ref="exercise-jogging-on-mt-hood">Checkpoint</xref>,
        we learned that a horizontal line's slope is
        <m>0\text{,}</m> because the distance doesn't change as time moves on.
        So the numerator in the <xref ref="definition-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref> is <m>0</m>.
        Now, if we know a line's slope and its <m>y</m>-intercept,
        we can use <xref ref="definition-slope-intercept-form" text="title">slope-intercept form</xref> to write its equation:
        <md permid="nFE">
          <mrow>y\amp=mx+b</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=0x+b</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=b</mrow>
        </md>
        This provides us with an alternative way to think about equations of horizontal lines.
        They have a certain <m>y</m>-intercept <m>b</m>,
        and they have slope <m>0</m>.
      </p>

      <p permid="XcS">
        We use horizontal lines to model scenarios where there is no change in <m>y</m>-values,
        like when Kato stopped for <m>12</m> hours (he deserved a rest)!
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="ncO">
      <title>Plotting Points</title>
      <webwork>
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
                @x=(-2..2);
                @y=(-4.25)x5;
                $pts=MultiAnswer(map{($_%2==0)?$x[$_/2]:$y[($_-1)/2]}(0..9))->with(
                  singleResult => 1,
                  allowBlankAnswers => 1,
                  checker => sub {
                    my ($correct,$student,$self) = @_;
                    my @sx = @{$student}[0,2,4,6,8];
                    my @sy = @{$student}[1,3,5,7,9];
                    my $OK=1;
                    if ($sy[0]!=-4.25) {
                        $self->setMessage(1,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $self->setMessage(2,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $OK=0;
                      }
                    for my $i(1..4){
                      if ($sy[$i]!=-4.25) {
                        $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $OK=0;
                      }
                      for my $j(0..$i-1){
                        if ($sy[$i]==-4.25 and $sx[$i]==$sx[$j]) {
                          $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point was already used.");
                          $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point was already used.");
                          $OK=0;
                        }
                      }
                    }
                    return $OK;
                  }
                );
                $gr = init_graph(-7,-7,7,7,axes=>[0,0],grid=>[14,14],size=>[240,240]);
                $gr->lb('reset');
                for $j (-6..-1,1..6) {
                   $gr->lb( new Label($j,   0,  $j,'black','center','top'  ,'large'));
                   $gr->lb( new Label( 0,  $j,  $j,'black','right','middle','large'));
                };
                $gr->lb( new Label(7, 0, "x ",'black','right','bottom','large'));
                $gr->lb( new Label(0, 7, " y",'black','left','top','large'));
                for my $i(-2..2){$gr->stamps( closed_circle($i,-4.25,'blue') );}
                $gr->moveTo(0,-4.25);
                $gr->arrowTo(-7,-4.25,'blue',1);
                $gr->moveTo(0,-4.25);
                $gr->arrowTo(7,-4.25,'blue',1);
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p permid="Qin">
              Suppose you need to plot the equation <m>y=-4.25</m>.
              Since the equation is in <q><m>y=</m></q> form,
              you decide to make a table of points.
              Fill out some points for this table.
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="JQl">

              <tabular permid="UwH">
                <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>

            </sidebyside>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="MZm">
            <p permid="LTT">
              We can use whatever values for <m>x</m> that we like,
              as long as they are all different.
              The equation tells us the <m>y</m>-value has to be <m>-4.25</m> each time.
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="pXu">

              <tabular permid="jFF">
                <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
