    <example permid="Fgs">
      <title>Slope of a Vertical Line</title>
      <p permid="Dkb">
        What is the slope of a vertical line?
        <xref ref="figure-vertical-lines">Figure</xref>
        shows three lines passing through the origin,
        each steeper than the last.
        In each graph, you can see a slope triangle that uses a
        <q>run</q> of <m>1</m> unit.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="figure-vertical-lines" permid="vFC">
        <caption />

        <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" permid="ClM">

          <image permid="ueK">
            <description>a line with a slope of 1/1=1</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,
                            ymin=-1,]
                    \addplot+[] coordinates {(-1,-1) (7,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.5] {$\text{slope}=\frac{1}{1}=1$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)} node[above,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,1)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image permid="alT">
            <description>a line with a slope of 2/1=2, which is steeper than the first line</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,
                            ymin=-1,]
                    \addplot+[] coordinates {(-0.5,-1) (3.5,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.5] {$\text{slope}=\frac{2}{1}=2$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)} node[above,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,2)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$2$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image permid="Gtc">
            <description>a line with a slope of 4/1=4, which is steeper than the previous two lines</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,
                            ymin=-1,]
                    \addplot+[] coordinates {(-0.25,-1) (1.75,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.75] {$\text{slope}=\frac{4}{1}=4$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)} node[above,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,4)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$4$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </sidebyside>

      </figure>

      <p permid="jrk">
        If we continued making the line steeper and steeper until it was vertical,
        the slope triangle would still have a
        <q>run</q> of <m>1</m>,
        but the <q>rise</q> would become larger and larger with no upper limit.
        The slope would be <m>m=\frac{\text{very large}}{1}</m>.
        Actually if the line is vertical, the <q>rise</q> segment we've drawn,
        will never intercept the line.
        So the slope of a vertical line can be thought of as
        <q>infinitely large.</q>
        We usually say that the slope of a vertical line is <em>undefined</em>.
        Some people say that a vertical line <em>has no slope.</em>
      </p>
    </example>

    <fact xml:id="fact-undefined-slope">
      <idx><h>slope</h><h>undefined</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The slope of a vertical line is undefined.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <remark permid="RuK">
      <p permid="RnG">
        Be careful not to mix up <q>no slope</q>
        (which means <q>its slope is undefined</q>)
        with <q>has slope <m>0</m>.</q>
        If a line has slope <m>0</m>,
        it <em>does</em> have a slope.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you are familiar with NBA basketball,
        some players wear number <m>0</m>.
        That's not the same thing as <q>not having a number</q>.
        This is similar to the situation with having slope <m>0</m>
        versus not having slope.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <exercise permid="TjX">
      <title>Plotting Points</title>
      <webwork>
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
                @x=(3.14)x5;
                @y=(-2..2);
                $pts=MultiAnswer(map{($_%2==0)?$x[$_/2]:$y[($_-1)/2]}(0..9))->with(
                  singleResult => 1,
                  allowBlankAnswers => 1,
                  checker => sub {
                    my ($correct,$student,$self) = @_;
                    my @sx = @{$student}[0,2,4,6,8];
                    my @sy = @{$student}[1,3,5,7,9];
                    my $OK=1;
                    if ($sx[0]!=3.14) {
                        $self->setMessage(1,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $self->setMessage(2,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $OK=0;
                      }
                    for my $i(1..4){
                      if ($sx[$i]!=3.14) {
