    <paragraphs permid="gDI">
      <title>Summary of Horizontal and Vertical Line Equations</title>
      <sidebyside permid="GVF">

        <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor" permid="gKZ">
          <col width="47%" right="medium"/>
          <col width="47%" />
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell>Horizontal Lines</cell>
            <cell>Vertical Lines</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>
              <p permid="VXz">
                A line is <term>horizontal</term>
                if and only if its equation can be written
                <me permid="TMN">
                  y=k
                </me>
                for some constant <m>k</m>.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p permid="CeI">
                A line is <term>vertical</term> if and only if its equation can be written
                <me permid="zTW">
                  x=h
                </me>
                for some constant <m>h</m>.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>
              <p permid="ilR">
                In <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref>,
                any line with equation
                <me permid="gbf">
                  0x+By=C
                </me>
                is horizontal.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p permid="Ota">
                In <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref>,
                any line with equation
                <me permid="Mio">
                  Ax+0y=C
                </me>
                is vertical.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>
              <p permid="uAj">
                If the line with equation <m>y=k</m> is horizontal,
                it has a <m>y</m>-intercept at <m>(0,k)</m> and has slope <m>0</m>.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p permid="aHs">
                If the line with equation <m>x=h</m> is vertical,
                it has an <m>x</m>-intercept at <m>(h,0)</m> and its slope is <em>undefined</em>.
                Some say it has <em>no</em> slope,
                and some say the slope is <em>infinitely large</em>.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
          <row bottom="none">
            <cell>
              <p permid="GOB">
                In the <xref ref="definition-slope-intercept-form" text="title">slope-intercept form</xref>,
                any line with equation
                <me permid="spx">
                  y=0x+b
                </me>
                is horizontal.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p permid="mVK">
                It's impossible to write the equation of a vertical line in <xref ref="definition-slope-intercept-form" text="title">slope-intercept form</xref>,
                because vertical lines do not have a defined slope.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>

      </sidebyside>
    </paragraphs>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsection-parallel-lines" permid="rcN">
    <title>Parallel Lines</title>
    <example permid="zrg">
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="LFy">
        <stack>
          <p permid="Uim">
            Two trees were planted in the same year,
            and their growth over time is modeled by the two lines in <xref ref="figure-trees">Figure</xref>.
            Use linear equations to model each tree's growth,
            and interpret their meanings in this context.
          </p>

          <p permid="Apv">
            We can see Tree 1's equation is
            <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+2\text{,}</m> and Tree 2's equation is
            <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+5\text{.}</m> Tree 1 was <m>2</m> feet tall when it was planted,
            and Tree 2 was <m>5</m> feet tall when it was planted.
            Both trees have been growing at the same rate,
            <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> feet per year,
            or <m>2</m> feet every <m>3</m> years.
          </p>
        </stack>

        <figure xml:id="figure-trees" permid="MDN">
          <caption>Two Trees' Growth Chart</caption>
          <image width="47%" permid="SHu">
            <description>This is a Cartesian grid with two parallel lines. Tree 1 has a slope triangle from (0,2) to (3,4) for a slope of 2/3. Tree 2 has a slope triangle from (0,5) to (3.7) for a slope of 2/3.</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xlabel={$x$ time in years},ylabel={$y$ height in feet},
                        xmin=-1,xmax=5,ymin=-1,ymax=9,
                        minor ytick=,
                        xtick={-1,0,...,4},ytick={-1,0,...,8}]

                        \addplot+[domain = 0:5,->]{2/3*x+2} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above] {Tree 1};
                        \addplot+[domain = 0:5,->]{2/3*x+5} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above] {Tree 2};

                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,2)} node[below right] {$(0,2)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,4)} node[below right] {$(3,4)$};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,2) (3,2)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,2) (3,3.7)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$2$};

                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[below right] {$(0,5)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,7)} node[below right] {$(3,7)$};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,5) (3,5)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,5) (3,6.7)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$2$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </sidebyside>

      <p permid="gwE">
        An important observation right now is that those two lines are parallel.
        Why?
        For lines with positive slopes,
        the bigger a line's slope, the steeper the line is slanted.
        As a result, if two lines have the same slope,
        they are slanted at the same angle, thus they are parallel.
      </p>
    </example>

    <fact xml:id="fact-parallel-lines" permid="fyp">
      <idx><h>parallel lines</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p permid="YSf">
          Any two vertical lines are parallel to each other.
          For two non-vertical lines,
          they are parallel if and only if they have the same slope.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <exercise permid="rMH">
      <webwork>
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
                Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                parser::Assignment->Allow;
                $line=Formula("y=17.2x+128.2");
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p permid="cwF">
              A line <m>\ell</m> is parallel to the line with equation <m>y=17.2x-340.9</m>,
              but <m>\ell</m> has <m>y</m>-intercept at <m>(0,128.2)</m>.
              What is an equation for <m>\ell</m>?
            </p>

            <p permid="IDO">
              <var name="$line" width="20" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="ZnE">
            <p permid="kwD">
              Parallel lines have the same slope,
              and the slope of <m>y=17.2x-340.9</m> is <m>17.2</m>.
              So <m>\ell</m> has slope <m>17.2</m>.
              And we have been given that <m>\ell</m>'s <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,128.2)</m>.
              So we can use slope-intercept form to write its equation as
              <me permid="YwG">
                y=17.2x+128.2\text{.}
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <exercise permid="XTQ">
      <webwork>
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
                Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                parser::Assignment->Allow;
                $line=Formula("y=-3.5(x+12)+23");
