      </sidebyside>

    </figure>

    <p permid="COC">
      The second line in <xref ref="figure-perpendicular-lines">Figure</xref> has slope
      <me permid="kKY">
        \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{-1}{m}=-\frac{1}{m}\text{.}
      </me>
    </p>

    <fact xml:id="fact-perpendicular-lines" permid="kii">
      <idx><h>perpendicular lines</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p permid="EZo">
          A vertical line and a horizontal line are perpendicular.
          For two lines that are neither vertical nor horizontal,
          they are perpendicular if and only if the slope of one is the negative reciprocal of the slope of the other.
          That is, if one has slope <m>m</m>,
          the other has slope <m>-\frac{1}{m}</m>.
        </p>

        <p permid="lgx">
          Another way to say this is that the product of the slopes of two perpendicular lines is <m>-1</m>
          (assuming both of the lines have a slope in the first place).
          That is, if there are two perpendicular lines and we let <m>m_1</m> and <m>m_2</m> represent their slopes,
          then <m>m_1\cdot m_2=-1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <p permid="iVL">
      Not convinced?
      Here are three pairs of perpendicular lines where we can see if the pattern holds.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%" margins="0%" permid="wwA">
      <figure permid="Lyu">
        <caption>Graphing <m>y=2x-2</m> and <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+2</m>. Note the relationship between their slopes: <m>2=-\frac{1}{-\sfrac{1}{2}}</m></caption>
        <image permid="rke">
          <description>the graph of lines y=2x-2 and y=-1/2x+2 showing that they are perpendicular lines.</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[axis equal]
                        \addplot+[domain = -2.5:4.5]{2*x-2} node[pos=0.15,sloped,above]{$y=2x-2$};
                        \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{-0.5*x+2} node[pos=0.15,sloped,above]{$y=-\frac{1}{2}x+2$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
        </image>

      </figure>

      <figure permid="rFD">
        <caption>Graphing <m>y=-3x+4</m> and <m>y=\frac{1}{3}x-3</m>. Note the relationship between their slopes: <m>-3=-\frac{1}{\sfrac{1}{3}}</m></caption>
        <image permid="Xrn">
          <description>the graph of lines y=-3x+4 and y=1/3x-3 showing that they are perpendicular.</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[axis equal]
                        \addplot+[domain = -1:3.666]{-3*x+4} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above]{$y=-3x+4$};
                        \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{1/3*x-3} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above]{$y=\frac{1}{3}x-3$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
        </image>

      </figure>

      <figure permid="XMM">
        <caption>Graphing <m>y=x</m> and <m>y=-x</m>. Note the relationship between their slopes: <m>1=-\frac{1}{-1}</m></caption>
        <image permid="Dyw">
          <description>the graph of lines y=x and y=-x showing that they are perpendicular</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[axis equal]
                        \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{x} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above]{$y=x$};
                        \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{-x} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above]{$y=-x$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
        </image>

      </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <example permid="EaZ">
      <statement>
        <p permid="sKW">
          Line <m>A</m> passes through <m>(-2,10)</m> and
          <m>(3,-10)\text{.}</m> Line <m>B</m> passes through <m>(-4,-4)</m> and
          <m>(8,-1)\text{.}</m> Determine whether these two lines are parallel,
          perpendicular or neither.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="gSd">
        <p permid="wKV">
          We will use the slope formula to find both lines' slopes:
          <md permid="QSh">
            <mrow>\text{Line }A\text{'s slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\amp\text{Line }B\text{'s slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10-10}{3-(-2)}\amp\amp=\frac{-1-(-4)}{8-(-4)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-20}{5}\amp\amp=\frac{3}{12}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-4\amp\amp=\frac{1}{4}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="cSe">
          Their slopes are not the same,
          so those two lines are not parallel.
        </p>

        <p permid="IZn">
          The product of their slopes is
          <m>(-4)\cdot\frac{1}{4}=-1\text{,}</m> which means the two lines are perpendicular.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="cDJ">
      <webwork>
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
                Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                parser::Assignment->Allow;
                $line=Formula("y=3/2(x-4)-3");
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p permid="AZp">
              Line <m>A</m> and Line <m>B</m> are perpendicular.
              Line <m>A</m>'s equation is
              <m>2x+3y=12\text{.}</m> Line <m>B</m> passes through the point
              <m>(4,-3)\text{.}</m> Find an equation for Line <m>B</m>.
            </p>

            <p permid="hgy">
              <var name="$line" width="20" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="lBW">
            <p permid="pgw">
              First, we will find Line <m>A</m>'s slope by rewriting its equation from standard form to slope-intercept form:
              <md permid="wZq">
                <mrow>2x+3y\amp=12</mrow>
                <mrow>3y\amp=12\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
                <mrow>3y\amp=-2x+12</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{-2x+12}{3}</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+4</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>

            <p permid="VnF">
              So Line <m>A</m>'s slope is
              <m>-\frac{2}{3}\text{.}</m> Since Line <m>B</m> is perpendicular to Line <m>A</m>,
              its slope is <m>-\frac{1}{-\frac{2}{3}}=\frac{3}{2}</m>.
              It's also given that Line <m>B</m> passes through
              <m>(4,-3)\text{,}</m> so we can write Line <m>B</m>'s point-slope form equation:
              <md permid="dgz">
                <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_0)+y_0</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=\frac{3}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

